00:04:56.390 --> 00:05:01.340
of passing interest in China and you're just
getting news about it from sound bites you

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:05.780
could easily come away with an idea that China
is an essentially homogenous place or largely

00:05:05.780 --> 00:05:10.810
homogenous place. What I try to say in the
book is that while it may be more homogenous

00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:15.819
in some specific ways than other places for
example, unlike the United States there aren't

00:05:15.819 --> 00:05:20.599
a lot of people who trace their descent back
to totally different parts of the world; unlike

00:05:20.599 --> 00:05:25.789
Indonesia there isn't quite the linguistic
variety there, it may not have as much religious

00:05:25.789 --> 00:05:31.190
variety as India. It may be less heterogeneous
in some ways than those places, but that's

00:05:31.190 --> 00:05:35.949
a far cry from saying it's largely homogenous.
It's in fact a very diverse place. And even

00:05:35.949 --> 00:05:40.690
some of the things that are thought of as
representing the largely homogeneousness of

00:05:40.690 --> 00:05:46.509
it when you push on it, start to collapse.
For example it is commonly said that 90% of

00:05:46.509 --> 00:05:52.060
Chinese belong to one ethnic group; the Han
Chinese. And that their 55, 50 some odd other

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:58.050
ethnic minorities, but they only comprise
10% of the population. But if you push harder

00:05:58.050 --> 00:06:03.261
on that and you look at the 90% Han figure,
you actually find that there are differences

00:06:03.261 --> 00:06:08.190
among the Han that in another setting we would
describe as ethnic differences. The way in

00:06:08.190 --> 00:06:14.000
which urban Chinese often talk about people
from the countryside, who like them are Han,

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:19.220
involves all the stereotyping and notions
of being of a lesser quality, is a term that

00:06:19.220 --> 00:06:24.889
is sometimes use, that we would think, that
we would associate with ethnic or racial prejudice.

00:06:24.889 --> 00:06:29.520
There's also a group called the Hakka which
literally means guest people, which are Han

00:06:29.520 --> 00:06:33.690
Chinese who moved from northern China to Southern
China quite a long time ago and are scattered

00:06:33.690 --> 00:06:39.289
out, they speak a completely different dialect
than the people living right near them. Ah,

00:06:39.289 --> 00:06:44.479
in the 19th century when a lot of Han Chinese
women bound their feet, or at least in some

00:06:44.479 --> 00:06:48.259
settings a lot did; the Hakka women never
bound their feet. So they had this kind of

00:06:48.259 --> 00:06:52.940
cultural difference that in another setting
might be thought of as ethnic. There were

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:57.389
feuds sometimes, violence between Hakka and
non-Hakka living near each other. In another

00:06:57.389 --> 00:07:01.380
setting that would be thought of as inter-ethnic
violence, so that's just the kind of diversity

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:07.520
within there. There's also religious diversity,
diversity based on region and locale. Local

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:11.930
identities become very important in China.
Gender, how people are experienced changes

00:07:11.930 --> 00:07:16.139
in China. It's very different when people
ask me how Chinese feel about 'X'. These are

00:07:16.139 --> 00:07:20.550
the kinds of things I break down. You know,
do you mean male Chinese or female? Do you

00:07:20.550 --> 00:07:25.490
mean living near the sea coast where the cities
have been booming, or in the more hinterland

00:07:25.490 --> 00:07:31.310
areas where the cities are hoping to boom
soon? Do you mean, what are you talking about?

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:36.159
But often what I come down to most, and this
is one section that I'll read a short passage

00:07:36.159 --> 00:07:42.099
about, is age differences that I think I really
want to know how old are these Chinese that

00:07:42.099 --> 00:07:47.080
you want me to say what's their attitude toward
America or something like that. And these

00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:52.949
are just some images that go along with this
talk. So one of the questions that I ask in

00:07:52.949 --> 00:07:58.789
the book and then answer is how important
are age divides in China? Generation gaps

00:07:58.789 --> 00:08:02.710
are present in every part of the world, but
the speed with which China has changed in

00:08:02.710 --> 00:08:07.910
the past several decades makes the one in
the PRC a chasm of unusual size. Here are

00:08:07.910 --> 00:08:14.960
some basic facts worth noting. In 2007 more
than 40% of the citizen of PRC were under

00:08:14.960 --> 00:08:21.319
30 years old. More than 20% were 15 or younger.
Meaning that for close to half the people

00:08:21.319 --> 00:08:27.659
alive in China today, Mao has always been
dead. And for roughly a quarter of them the

00:08:27.659 --> 00:08:32.729
Berlin Wall has always been rubble.
Switching from political to social issues

00:08:32.729 --> 00:08:38.229
more than half of all Chinese were never alive
in a China that did not have a large divide

00:08:38.229 --> 00:08:42.050
separating those who have benefitted most
from the reforms and those that have been

00:08:42.050 --> 00:08:47.970
left behind by them. While those between 30
and 65 have a memory of more egalitarian times

00:08:47.970 --> 00:08:53.480
that have disappeared. And those older than
that may have a, may see the current disparities

00:08:53.480 --> 00:08:58.339
between the haves and have not's as a return
to a socially divided, economically divided

00:08:58.339 --> 00:09:03.589
landscape that they knew in their youth that
then had disappeared and has now come back.

00:09:03.589 --> 00:09:08.100
In cultural terms, most middle aged urban
parents are people who until they were in

00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:13.370
their 30's never made a private phone call
or rode in a car. For the main phones were

00:09:13.370 --> 00:09:18.589
still shared neighborhood ones and the main
urban vehicle; still bicycles and buses, as

00:09:18.589 --> 00:09:24.430
recently as the mid 1980's which was the first
time I lived in China. And yet these people

00:09:24.430 --> 00:09:29.200
have children who have always had mobile phones
and think nothing of hailing cabs, at least

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:34.140
those living in cities. This generation gap
influences an enormous number of things, from

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:38.720
attitudes toward the pace of modern life,
this can seem unsettling to some and bracing

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:44.700
to others; to views of China's place in the
world. And it affects phenomena that are presented,

00:09:44.700 --> 00:09:50.360
often in the sound bite driven commentary,
and even in Chinese media as well, as transcending

00:09:50.360 --> 00:09:55.880
generations. Consider for example the supposedly
timeless Chinese attachment to quote unquote

00:09:55.880 --> 00:10:02.120
Confucian values; such as social harmony.
The oldest residents of the PRC can remember

00:10:02.120 --> 00:10:06.550
a time when China was governed by a
non-communist regime, that of Chiang Kai-Shek

00:10:06.550 --> 00:10:11.430
that venerated Confucius and made much of
the need to follow his moral dictates. For

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:16.160
Chinese born between the mid to late 1940's
and early 1960's by contrast, the current

00:10:16.160 --> 00:10:20.680
celebration of Confucius and his ideas may
seem a bit odd, since they may remember mass

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:27.060
campaigns to criticize all vestiges of Confucianthought.
But for Chinese born recently who are unfamiliar

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:31.390
with this history, it is often ignored or
glossed over in school books and their parents

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:35.620
sometimes prefer not to talk about it. There's
nothing remarkable at all about President

00:10:35.620 --> 00:10:43.970
Hu Jintao's claim that communism and Confucianism
are compatible rather than opposite ideas.

00:10:43.970 --> 00:10:50.329
So these are some images that would seem ordinary
to some Chinese of a certain age and extraordinary

00:10:50.329 --> 00:10:54.149
for others, things people they thought they
would never see, things that they've simply

00:10:54.149 --> 00:10:59.040
always seen. These are fashion magazines and
modern lifestyle magazines that in Mao's day

00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:03.490
would be considered a kind of banned literature
because they promoted bourgeois materialist

00:11:03.490 --> 00:11:08.900
values. But now Chinese who are in their 20's
have just grown up always seeing style and

00:11:08.900 --> 00:11:13.079
fashion magazines and don't think of it as
something that at any point would be viewed

00:11:13.079 --> 00:11:20.260
as dangerous. And so forth.
All right. This is the Orwell vs. Huxley side

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:26.041
of things that I treated in my last book,
my book before last, "China's Brave New World

00:11:26.041 --> 00:11:31.440
and Other Tales for Global Times". But I revisit
in this one in part, in part because I got

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:35.790
something wrong, or I didn't go far enough
in one part of it and so I get to correct

00:11:35.790 --> 00:11:43.110
this with a new book. Um, the basic idea is
that if you think about these two books that

00:11:43.110 --> 00:11:47.510
are often taught together or talked about
together as providing two different dystopian

00:11:47.510 --> 00:11:52.890
views of the future, is that there are two
different views of authoritarian rule. Ah,

00:11:52.890 --> 00:11:57.232
Huxley's, in Orwell's' view which has become
the most famous or most talked about in the

00:11:57.232 --> 00:12:01.380
United States, certainly the one talked about
most to China, in regard to China, is a Big

00:12:01.380 --> 00:12:05.160
Brother state where the government is watching
you, where the people are kept in line through

00:12:05.160 --> 00:12:10.361
fear, and where the government forces you
to believe whatever it says, so they can force

00:12:10.361 --> 00:12:17.199
you to believe that 2+2=5. It's a hard form
of authoritarianism that governs by fear.

00:12:17.199 --> 00:12:23.029
In Huxley's "Brave New World" which was written
earlier, that actually Huxley was a teacher

00:12:23.029 --> 00:12:30.029
of Orwell's' at Eden which is an interesting
little side fact. Um in Huxley's "Brave New

00:12:30.029 --> 00:12:35.370
World", people are kept in line in a different
way, by the government playing to their pleasures

00:12:35.370 --> 00:12:41.411
and their desires. So in Huxley's vision of
the future, people are kept docile through

00:12:41.411 --> 00:12:47.459
Soma, this bliss inducing drug that's readily
available, through the feelies which are these

00:12:47.459 --> 00:12:54.810
sort of high level immersive pornographic
forms of entertainment. So there's sort of

00:12:54.810 --> 00:13:01.620
this way in which people don't rise up because
their blissed out and kept very busy and also

00:13:01.620 --> 00:13:07.029
divided from one other based on lifestyles.
Whereas in the 1984 world, everybody's in

00:13:07.029 --> 00:13:12.579
the same boat but they don't rise up because
of fear, what will happen to them. So I think

00:13:12.579 --> 00:13:16.990
these are useful to think about these two
visions of the future. And Orwell and Huxley

00:13:16.990 --> 00:13:23.269
when they were alive argued about which of
them they thought were the better prediction.

00:13:23.269 --> 00:13:29.230
So with China, it's often thought of in Orwellian
terms. And when Huxley was talking, when he

00:13:29.230 --> 00:13:33.670
was criticized in 1984, he said I don't think
the style of boot on the face rule that you

00:13:33.670 --> 00:13:39.149
describe is really what the dictators of the
future will use. So in China there clearly

00:13:39.149 --> 00:13:44.610
are moments and places in which the boot on
the face is exactly um, the way that control

00:13:44.610 --> 00:13:50.423
is exercised. But I think a lot of control
or what keeps people from taking to the streets,

00:13:50.423 --> 00:13:54.221
and it's not just in China, but throughout
the 21st Century, a lot of what's going on

00:13:54.221 --> 00:14:01.449
is much more what Huxley was describing; a
society of the spectacle and of hedonism in

00:14:01.449 --> 00:14:08.589
which people are too busy in various ways
to take political action and are kind of dulled

00:14:08.589 --> 00:14:14.410
or satisfied, so the manipulation of pleasure
rather than fear can often keep people. One

00:14:14.410 --> 00:14:19.019
of the things to think about with Huxley vs.
Orwell, is that Orwell encourages you to think

00:14:19.019 --> 00:14:23.720
about who's watching you, and Huxley encourages
you to think about what you're watching and

00:14:23.720 --> 00:14:27.759
what keeps you busy, and if you think about
the internet story, we can get back to that

00:14:27.759 --> 00:14:32.070
as well. There's a side of censorship and
control by the Government, there's also a

00:14:32.070 --> 00:14:37.730
side of the Internet in China, as the Internet
in other places, if you go to an Internet

00:14:37.730 --> 00:14:41.980
Cafe in China, you don't find a lot of um,
young people trying to get around the great

00:14:41.980 --> 00:14:47.670
firewall and read off limit sites. There may
be some, but you find a lot of people playing

00:14:47.670 --> 00:14:53.399
first person shooter games, which could arguably
be one of the forms of Soma of the present

00:14:53.399 --> 00:15:00.051
day. Now in, in my book, what I talked about
in the earlier book, I talked about China

00:15:00.051 --> 00:15:06.930
going through 1984 periods and Brave New World
periods, which in Chinese someone is talking

00:15:06.930 --> 00:15:11.250
about tightening and loosening of political
controls, so I said 1989, when there was a

00:15:11.250 --> 00:15:16.991
massacre that put an end to protests in Beijing,
and scores of other cities, and then the government

00:15:16.991 --> 00:15:22.920
came out and said there was no massacre. There
was just, there were just rioters that were

00:15:22.920 --> 00:15:27.570
quelled by very restrained kinds of troups
and you'd better believe this. That was an

00:15:27.570 --> 00:15:33.149
Orwellian moment, the government were saying,
with its big lie 2+2=5 and you better believe

00:15:33.149 --> 00:15:40.069
it. Fairly soon after that there was this
loosening up of political controls and I think

00:15:40.069 --> 00:15:45.220
there was more of a Brave New World moment.
And there was a lot of focus on consumerism,

00:15:45.220 --> 00:15:49.649
what was keeping people from going back on
the street maybe partly fear, but partly that

00:15:49.649 --> 00:15:56.100
they were busy indulging in new pleasures.
So I talked about this temporal side of this,

00:15:56.100 --> 00:15:59.779
these two paradigms, but what I didn't talk
about is that there's also this geographical

00:15:59.779 --> 00:16:02.759
side, and I wanted to read a brief part on
that.

00:16:02.759 --> 00:16:07.390
So there's an ebbing and flowing of hard and
soft forms of authoritarianism over time in

00:16:07.390 --> 00:16:13.130
China, but there's also a geographical dimension.
In areas with significantly large and periodically

00:16:13.130 --> 00:16:19.530
restive non-Han populations such as Xinjiang
and Tibet, the modes of control tend to remain

00:16:19.530 --> 00:16:25.790
much more 1984, even when the country as a
whole is in a Brave New World mode. Conversely

00:16:25.790 --> 00:16:30.790
in booming East Coast cities such as Shanghai
with their cultures of distraction, epitomize

00:16:30.790 --> 00:16:36.040
by public spaces dominated by massive video
screens and their glittering department stores,

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:41.480
Huxley tends to be a better guide. It's no
surprise these pictures were taken by me in

00:16:41.480 --> 00:16:48.500
Shanghai. And so far while Brave New World
and 1984 have some relevance in a place like

00:16:48.500 --> 00:16:54.050
Shanghai though it's more Brave New World,
in the former colonies of Hong Kong and Macau,

00:16:54.050 --> 00:17:00.250
they have never, since becoming part of the
PRC in 1997, been subjected fully to 1984

00:17:00.250 --> 00:17:04.670
like suppression. And that's another thing
is that to think about the degree of regional

00:17:04.670 --> 00:17:09.210
variation and of course that's something I
don't need to say here, because with the internet

00:17:09.210 --> 00:17:14.050
what goes on in Hong Kong is totally different
from what goes on in the mainland. But publishing

00:17:14.050 --> 00:17:18.830
is very different, there'll be no problem
at all for this book to be sold in the bookstores

