we think abut in many parts of the world there's
a digital divide, that's is a common term

00:17:45.430 --> 00:17:50.330
for either people who go online or people
who don't go online. With China it's crucial

00:17:50.330 --> 00:17:55.570
to think of multiple digital divides that
separate out people geographic area, you're

00:17:55.570 --> 00:18:00.140
going online in Hong Kong, or the Mainland.
But beyond that are you going online and using

00:18:00.140 --> 00:18:05.180
VPN servers that allow you to surf the web
by fooling your computer into thinking it's

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:10.930
going on from someplace else. In which case,
the fact that, what's happened with Google

00:18:10.930 --> 00:18:17.510
is much, much less relevant than if you aren't
using a VPN server. If you used a VPN server

00:18:17.510 --> 00:18:21.890
you could still be going on, on Google and
searching through the American version or

00:18:21.890 --> 00:18:26.501
whatever. So there's a divide between people
who go online, people who don't go online,

00:18:26.501 --> 00:18:32.560
people who go online and don't go around the
firewalls, people who go online and are somewhat

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:37.090
creative going around and trying to get to
sites that are off limits, people who simply

00:18:37.090 --> 00:18:42.950
go on always using a VPN that is allowing
them to use the Net much more like the way

00:18:42.950 --> 00:18:46.940
people in the United States are using the
Net than the people down the street might

00:18:46.940 --> 00:18:52.850
be using the Net who don't have the technological
savvy or the interest to do that. Another

00:18:52.850 --> 00:18:57.390
thing is the term that has taken off for talking
about control for the Chinese Internet is

00:18:57.390 --> 00:19:04.800
the Great Firewall which I think is a clever
term. It invokes a famous symbol of China.

00:19:04.800 --> 00:19:12.300
It encourages us to think, its lead to some
clever new language by Chinese bloggers who

00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:18.220
talk about climbing the Great Firewall. It's
talked about once upon a time Reagan said

00:19:18.220 --> 00:19:23.560
Gorbachev tear down that wall and now that
there should be America say tear down that

00:19:23.560 --> 00:19:27.690
Great Firewall, you know, so there's a lot
of word play and interesting things with that.

00:19:27.690 --> 00:19:33.490
But I think it encouraged us to view China
too exotically if we don't interrogate it.

00:19:33.490 --> 00:19:40.020
And a term I like is what Jeremy Goldkorn
who's one of the most astute analysts of the

00:19:40.020 --> 00:19:45.540
Chinese internet and runs a great website
in Beijing called danwei.org. He refers to

00:19:45.540 --> 00:19:50.710
the Net Nanny. He refers to the Chinese state
as not so much, don't think of it as trying

00:19:50.710 --> 00:19:56.700
to wall off access of information, think of
it as trying to steer users of the Chinese

00:19:56.700 --> 00:20:00.530
Internet toward the healthy sites and away
from the unhealthy ones, much like a nanny

00:20:00.530 --> 00:20:06.311
would. And think of China as doing things
that aren't uniquely Chinese but have a lot

00:20:06.311 --> 00:20:12.370
in common with the Internet in other settings
where certain things that are deemed dangerous

00:20:12.370 --> 00:20:19.430
or not fit for children or others might be
kept off limits. I mean there are limits on

00:20:19.430 --> 00:20:24.360
pornography in many places, there are limits
on certain kinds of speech in smaller areas,

00:20:24.360 --> 00:20:29.380
and there are places where there's limits
on a lot that goes on in the Internet, places

00:20:29.380 --> 00:20:34.330
like Iran obviously but also places like Saudi
Arabia and Singapore where we can think about

00:20:34.330 --> 00:20:37.460
the nanny as being a useful way to proceed.

