00:31:21.150 --> 00:31:26.870
capita user of greenhouse gases. You should
do something about it first. To a lot of the

00:31:26.870 --> 00:31:30.350
rest of the world, we're the two countries
that are going to have to figure out some

00:31:30.350 --> 00:31:36.050
way to rein in our enviromental to do something
about the environment. Together along with

00:31:36.050 --> 00:31:40.081
some other big countries. So first of all
with a lot of issues, what we have in common

00:31:40.081 --> 00:31:45.210
seems more striking than what sets us apart
today. I first started thinking about this

00:31:45.210 --> 00:31:50.800
when I went to Sweden to give a talk about
10 years ago on U.S., China human rights issues.

00:31:50.800 --> 00:31:56.351
And I had a whole talk prepared about the
contrasts between our particular focus on

00:31:56.351 --> 00:32:01.720
some rights, and the UN's universal human
rights package, like religious freedom loom

00:32:01.720 --> 00:32:06.340
very large for us. In China at that time,
social and economic rights looms very large,

00:32:06.340 --> 00:32:11.220
and I was going to talk how these fit in to
our histories and traditions. But I was interviewed

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:16.880
by a Swedish student radio station. And they
said, so when you talk about U.S.-China human

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:20.650
rights, you're going to talk about the human
rights issue that we in Sweden often think

00:32:20.650 --> 00:32:26.580
of China and the U.S. being in the same category.
I said I don't know, what exactly do you have

00:32:26.580 --> 00:32:33.160
in mind. Well, you both have legalized executions.
So the death penalty was thought of there

00:32:33.160 --> 00:32:38.930
as having--. This was just something that
was eye opening, as a lot of times when you

00:32:38.930 --> 00:32:42.920
have discussions outside of China and the
U.S. and you see that we are thought of as

00:32:42.920 --> 00:32:47.850
two continent-sized countries that have always
talked about how much we hate imperialism.

00:32:47.850 --> 00:32:52.310
That seem to have managed to have, over time,
extend our territorial control. There is a

00:32:52.310 --> 00:32:56.580
lot of ways in which we are put in the same
category. But what I talk about more in the

00:32:56.580 --> 00:33:03.100
book, is how China today has a lot in common
with the United States, at the period when

00:33:03.100 --> 00:33:09.990
we were a rapidly industrializing, rapidly
urbanizing, rising economic power, that was

00:33:09.990 --> 00:33:15.930
being seen as a really challenge to the previous
existing powers. So the United States from

00:33:15.930 --> 00:33:23.820
the 1870s to the 1930s. Prior to that the
empires, the British Empire and the French

00:33:23.820 --> 00:33:29.230
Empire these were the major powers in the
world. London and Paris were the leading cities

00:33:29.230 --> 00:33:33.290
in the world. The United States cities were
rising up and one of the ways they were rising

00:33:33.290 --> 00:33:39.870
up and challenging those cities place in the
world was by hosting world's fairs. The descendents

00:33:39.870 --> 00:33:43.350
of which are World's Expo, Shanghai is just
hosting one.

00:33:43.350 --> 00:33:48.460
Our railways were impressing the world, much
like the railways of China are now. So one

00:33:48.460 --> 00:33:53.950
of the last questions I bring up is what kinds
of things do China and the United States have

00:33:53.950 --> 00:33:58.980
in common. What other things. This comes after
the comment on Sweden. There are many other

00:33:58.980 --> 00:34:03.360
parallels, some of which concern precisely
the things that Americans are fond of criticizing

00:34:03.360 --> 00:34:09.159
about the PRC. For example, as Peter Hessler,
one of my favorite writers on China has noted

00:34:09.159 --> 00:34:13.770
in an article about the instant cities of
China, where many factories use machines which

00:34:13.770 --> 00:34:18.400
are pirated versions of U.S. ones. The United
States' industrial take-off was fueled in

00:34:18.400 --> 00:34:23.270
part by just this sort of reverse engineering
that allowed businessmen in early U.S. boom

00:34:23.270 --> 00:34:28.950
towns to make use, for free, of patented British
technologies. And as the US historian Stephen

00:34:28.950 --> 00:34:33.700
Mihm has pointed out, in the late 1800's,
it was the United States, that was often seen

00:34:33.700 --> 00:34:39.010
by Europeans as China is often seen now by
Americans. As a place that produced inferior

00:34:39.010 --> 00:34:45.330
and sometimes downright dangerous goods, and
issues pirated editions of best sellers. Dickens

00:34:45.330 --> 00:34:49.650
complained bitterly about how many unauthorized
versions of his books were sold across the

00:34:49.650 --> 00:34:54.540
Atlantic when he came here. Something else
the countries have in common is that between

00:34:54.540 --> 00:34:59.480
the late 1800s and mid 1900s the United States
built railways and highway systems on a grand

00:34:59.480 --> 00:35:03.510
scale, which connected parts of the country
that were previously cut off from one another

00:35:03.510 --> 00:35:08.540
and were sometimes hailed as engineering marvels.
That was also the era when the United States

00:35:08.540 --> 00:35:14.730
hosted its first World's Fairs and it's first
Olympics. And as Susan Brownell, sports anthropologist

00:35:14.730 --> 00:35:20.130
reminds us, when the United States first got
to hold the games in 1904, and previously

00:35:20.130 --> 00:35:25.980
the event had only been held in Europe, some
foreign commentators assumed as they did again

00:35:25.980 --> 00:35:31.040
during the lead up to 2008 that the IOC had
made a terrible mistake in letting the Olympics

