00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:44.860
So I like to end by showing, I'll read one
final bit from the book, before that when

00:38:44.860 --> 00:38:51.460
I show this picture now, I like to reattach
with my academic side, and this makes me think

00:38:51.460 --> 00:38:52.910
of a quote by Homer...Simpson.

00:38:52.910 --> 00:38:56.230
[Audience laughter]

00:38:56.230 --> 00:39:01.850
He said, "Children are our future, unless
we stop them now." And I think the American

00:39:01.850 --> 00:39:06.410
attitude toward China has gone from saying
there's like sort of, if only they could learn

00:39:06.410 --> 00:39:11.740
from us, and they could become more like us,
and they could grow to be kind of this adult

00:39:11.740 --> 00:39:16.750
nation among nations, that would be great.
To now worrying about what's gonna happen

00:39:16.750 --> 00:39:24.201
to us once they are this full-fledged power.
But I need to end with the last question in

00:39:24.201 --> 00:39:28.820
the book. So I think this is important especially
after I talk about similarities. Is talking

00:39:28.820 --> 00:39:32.550
about similarities between China and the U.S.,
does this, is this an argument for Americans

00:39:32.550 --> 00:39:38.990
to refrain from all criticism of China, and
I say No. I want to emphasize this. Increased

00:39:38.990 --> 00:39:43.650
awareness of similarities such as those just
noted need not prevent or even discourage

00:39:43.650 --> 00:39:47.830
Americans from criticizing things that occur
in China. And when I get a chance to be interviewed

00:39:47.830 --> 00:39:52.020
on radio I'll try to, whatever the topic is,
to slip in something about something that

00:39:52.020 --> 00:39:57.760
concerns me in China like the sentencing of
Liu Xiaobo for an internet petition to 11

00:39:57.760 --> 00:40:05.630
years in prison, which I think is something
we should criticize. But while acknowledging

00:40:05.630 --> 00:40:09.260
similarities shouldn't stop us from criticizing
things that occur in China, or necessarily

00:40:09.260 --> 00:40:15.040
stop Chinese from criticizing things in America.
It could change how we go about doing this.

00:40:15.040 --> 00:40:19.830
It suggests that, as Stephen Mihm, the American
extraordinaire, I quoted before puts it, "if

00:40:19.830 --> 00:40:23.530
we want to understand how to deal with China
we could do worse than look at our own history

00:40:23.530 --> 00:40:29.610
as a guide." And he says when Americans take
the PRC to task for certain things, "a bit

00:40:29.610 --> 00:40:35.060
of empathy might even be in order." If the
residents of each super power thought as much

00:40:35.060 --> 00:40:38.680
about how much they have in common as what
makes them different it could even help increase

00:40:38.680 --> 00:40:44.160
the odds that whichever way criticisms fly
across the Pacific, they will be delivered

00:40:44.160 --> 00:40:48.710
in a less arrogant and patronizing fashion
than has sometimes been the case in the past.

00:40:48.710 --> 00:40:53.420
Another thing that could help ease U.S.-China
misunderstandings would simply be for people

00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:58.040
in each country to know more about the people
living in the other. I hope that U.S. readers

00:40:58.040 --> 00:41:02.390
who have made it to the end of this book feel
that they now know a few more things about

00:41:02.390 --> 00:41:06.740
the people of the PRC than they did when they
read its first pages. And I look forward to

00:41:06.740 --> 00:41:10.920
the day when I can point my Chinese friends
toward a comparable work that tries to tell

00:41:10.920 --> 00:41:16.450
them in a similar spirit of seeking to normalize
the experiences of a large and exotic seeming

00:41:16.450 --> 00:41:20.970
anti-imperialist empire that stands by the
